snippet.textDisplay: The several times I've had lasagna in Italy, the ragù had almost no tomato in it and it was always a disappointing homogeny of soft texture (with maybe a little crispiness on top) and the whole thing just tasted like béchamel. This one looks better because it's more tomato-heavy but I think American lasagna may be the one dish that improves the traditional Italian version.
snippet.textOriginal: The several times I've had lasagna in Italy, the ragù had almost no tomato in it and it was always a disappointing homogeny of soft texture (with maybe a little crispiness on top) and the whole thing just tasted like béchamel. This one looks better because it's more tomato-heavy but I think American lasagna may be the one dish that improves the traditional Italian version.

snippet.textDisplay: OK. Major Hack for you guys. Cook a huuuuuuuge pot of Bolognese Ragou and then can it in mason ball jars. The sauce will stay good for ever if you can it right. And now whenever you feel like Lasagne you just open one or two jars of homemade Bolognese Ragou and you're good to go. It is one time effort but then it is really nice to have on hand.
